  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">When a session opens with a document ID, the AI system prompt contains text from that document (verified by inspecting system prompt in debug logging with ADR-015 compliant log level)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When a document exceeds 30K tokens, only chunks fitting within the budget are selected (no context window overflow)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">When the user asks about section 8 of a long document after initially asking about section 1, the system prompt for the second turn contains section 8 chunks (conversation-aware re-selection)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">DocumentContextService is NOT registered in the DI container — verify by checking the AiModule/ServiceCollectionExtensions registrations remain at current count</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">No document chunk text appears in application logs at any log level (ADR-015 compliance)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">SpeFileStore is the only file retrieval mechanism used — no direct GraphServiceClient calls in DocumentContextService</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet build` passes with no errors introduced by this task</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The 30K token budget for document context is one part of the overall 128K context window. The full
    breakdown is roughly: 8K playbook context, 30K document context, ~40K conversation history, ~50K
    model response headroom. Never let the sum exceed 128K — `DocumentContextService` should enforce its
    own 30K limit and trust `PlaybookChatContextProvider` to enforce the overall budget.

    If `SemanticDocumentChunker` does not exist in `Services/Ai/TextExtraction/`, look for an equivalent
    class that wraps Document Intelligence chunking output. Do not implement paragraph-based chunking from
    scratch — reuse existing extraction infrastructure. Document the actual class name used in
    `notes/011-document-context-classes.md` for downstream tasks R2-012 and R2-013 to reference.

    Task R2-012 (multi-document) will extend this class — design `InjectDocumentContextAsync` with a
    single document ID to keep the interface simple; R2-012 will add the multi-document overload.
  </notes>

